[start section id="20102"]

Distal rectal mass.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Morse is a 56-year-old gentleman who presents for treatment of a rectal mass.  Mr. Morse underwent his first colonoscopy February 4, 2010, for screening purposes. A 4-cm mass was noted in the distal rectum with biopsies positive for villous adenoma with low-grade dysplasia.  This is described as a sessile, large, flat, distal rectal polyp.  Cold biopsies only were obtained to allow for further treatment.  No cancer staging has been performed, and Mr. Morse is asymptomatic with no hematochezia, melena, changes to bowel habit or narrowed stool caliber.  His family history is involved by a sister with colon polyps at age 53.
Comorbidities include hypertension, hyperlipidemia for which he uses medications.  He has no history of chest pains, chest pressures, shortness-of-breath, thrombosis or glaucoma.  He does not smoke and has no medication allergies.  He does; however, have a history of syncopal episodes historically occurring ten years ago in the ophthalmologist's office.  This episode is described as feeling lightheaded and blacking out for a couple of seconds.  There is no accompanying chest pains or heart palpitations.
During the course of our visit when standing up, Mr. Morse developed another syncopal episode, his second such episode.  As before, he described feeling lightheaded, he lost consciousness for approximately two seconds, and then came to.  He sustained no head trauma and was guided to the floor for examination.  His heart rate remained stable, and his blood pressure was stable at 110/70, although he was feeling back to normal when this was obtained.  He developed diaphoresis.  There was no evidence of seizures or other neurological complaints.  The episode was very short-lived, and the patient was conversant throughout.

[end section id="20103"]

